14:53.440 --> 14:56.399
just as much to lose
as we got to lose.

14:56.600 --> 14:58.114
I don't know what you mean.

14:58.600 --> 15:00.273
Well, we make a deal, Danny.

15:00.480 --> 15:03.678
Uh, you do us a favour,
and we do you a favour.

15:03.880 --> 15:05.678
Hey, sure, name it.
What favour?

15:05.880 --> 15:07.314
A contract.

15:07.920 --> 15:09.877
You... You mean
kill a man?

15:10.080 --> 15:11.753
Oh, Danny, a contract.

15:12.280 --> 15:13.999
You wanna call it kill,
you call it kill.

15:14.200 --> 15:15.998
Personally,
I don't like the word.

15:17.120 --> 15:19.032
Well... Well, who would it be?

15:19.240 --> 15:23.473
It would be the man
who killed your father.

15:24.480 --> 15:25.960
Oh, this is some heat over here.

15:26.160 --> 15:28.755
The man who killed my father?
No, that's impossible.

15:29.640 --> 15:33.953
My father committed suicide.
Suicide? No, he didn't.

15:34.160 --> 15:36.675
Yes, godfather,
that's what they said.
The autopsy showed the...

15:36.880 --> 15:40.191
The autopsy showed?
Oh, Danny, no.

15:40.400 --> 15:42.073
Your father was killed.

15:42.280 --> 15:45.830
You know, I've been coming
over here for 23 years
to open up my pores.

15:46.040 --> 15:49.033
What I wanna know is
what is so terrific about
opening your pores?

15:49.240 --> 15:50.240
Who killed him?

15:50.400 --> 15:52.241
I mean, do people walk
down the street and say,

15:52.280 --> 15:55.478
"Look at him, how nice.
Look at those nice, open pores"?

15:55.680 --> 15:57.637
No. "Nice hat."
"Nice haircut."

15:57.840 --> 16:01.151
They say nothing about the pores.
Who killed my father?

16:02.520 --> 16:06.309
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
It's all right. It's all right.

16:06.880 --> 16:09.520
Danny, now, we gonna tell you

16:09.760 --> 16:13.595
who killed your father
when you agree to do the job

16:13.800 --> 16:15.234
and not before, huh?

16:15.440 --> 16:17.511
Now, Danny, come on,
you kiss the ring,

16:17.720 --> 16:19.521
because Sheldon and I
got some business, okay?

16:19.720 --> 16:21.200
Ow!

16:23.320 --> 16:25.960
Boy. This is a lot
for one day.

16:26.160 --> 16:27.753
All right, all right.
Goodbye, Danny.

16:27.960 --> 16:29.360
[SPEAKS IN ITALIAN]

16:31.960 --> 16:33.599
He thinks this is
a lot for one day?

16:33.800 --> 16:34.800
[SPEAKS IN ITALIAN]

16:34.960 --> 16:37.759
Wait until he finds out
the man he has to kill

16:38.040 --> 16:40.475
is his own stepfather.

16:40.680 --> 16:42.592
But he's a nice boy.

16:44.520 --> 16:46.000
[♫]

16:47.400 --> 16:49.437
[DOORBELL RINGS]

16:53.640 --> 16:54.640
Hi, Mrs. Campbell.

16:54.840 --> 16:56.274
Hi, Benson.
Nice to see you.

16:56.480 --> 16:58.119
Hi.

16:59.360 --> 17:00.953
Guess what, Benson.

17:01.160 --> 17:03.436
My long-lost son that
I haven't seen in 15 years

17:03.640 --> 17:05.279
is coming here tonight
for dinner.

17:05.480 --> 17:07.869
Wonderful. I'm the one
who makes the meals,

17:08.079 --> 17:12.313
I'm the one who sets the table,
and I'm always the last one to know.

17:12.520 --> 17:14.193
Hello, Daddy.

17:15.000 --> 17:17.390
Benson, this is all wrong.

17:17.599 --> 17:19.830
The avocado and the shrimp
should not be separated.

17:20.040 --> 17:21.554
The shrimp should go
in the avocado.

17:22.040 --> 17:24.680
Here, Tinkerbell, stuff it.

17:25.920 --> 17:28.276
I'm so nervous,
my hands are shaking.
I need a drink.

17:28.480 --> 17:30.000
Benson, I'll have
a vodka with a twist.

17:30.080 --> 17:31.878
Yes, sir.

17:40.520 --> 17:43.752
Hey, Benson? Could you
tell the Tates we're here?

17:44.080 --> 17:45.594
Very well.

17:47.680 --> 17:49.592
They're here!

17:53.440 --> 17:56.160
Hi, Mom. Hi, Dad.
Oh, Dad, listen, I need 10 bucks.

17:56.360 --> 17:58.113
What for?
I got a date.

17:58.320 --> 18:00.471
What do you mean you have a date?
You're 12 years old.

18:01.240 --> 18:02.390
I'm 14.

18:04.480 --> 18:07.439
Yes, he'll be 15 in October.

18:07.640 --> 18:09.597
Thanks, Dad.
Good night, Mom.

18:09.800 --> 18:12.156
Not too late.
Don't wait up.

18:13.800 --> 18:16.713
Are you sure he's 14?
Mm-hm.

18:16.920 --> 18:20.596
He was born October 28th, 1962.

18:20.800 --> 18:23.395
I always remember
that it was October of '62,

18:23.600 --> 18:25.637
because that was when
the washing machine broke

18:25.840 --> 18:28.071
and I had to go
to the Laundromat that week.

18:28.280 --> 18:32.274
And I went into labour
between wash and spin dry.

18:33.880 --> 18:37.271
Uh, what are you
looking at, Chester?

18:37.920 --> 18:39.991
You. You look terrific.

18:40.200 --> 18:41.600
Oh! Heh-heh.

18:41.800 --> 18:44.110
Is that the glow you noticed?

18:44.320 --> 18:51.033
Well, uh, you see,
it's this new makeup that I'm
wearing that I'm allergic to.

18:51.240 --> 18:54.836
You see, it sort of
gives off this glowing effect,

18:55.040 --> 18:57.077
which, of course,
it's not supposed to do.

18:57.280 --> 18:59.272
It's just that it's the allergy.

18:59.480 --> 19:04.271
Uh, I... Chester, could we
go downstairs now?

19:04.480 --> 19:06.119
Because, you see,
the Campbells are here

19:06.320 --> 19:09.438
and the food's gonna get
overcooked and Benson's
gonna have a fit.

19:09.640 --> 19:12.235
But if you're not, uh...

19:12.440 --> 19:15.000
If you're not ready,
I'll just go down first,

19:15.200 --> 19:17.271
and you come when you're ready,

19:17.480 --> 19:20.917
which is probably
a better idea anyway.

19:22.160 --> 19:24.117
[♫]

19:25.840 --> 19:28.309
My son, my son.

19:28.520 --> 19:31.194
After 15 years,
I'm gonna be with my son.

19:31.400 --> 19:33.915
I mean, I'm so nervous,
I need another drink.

19:34.440 --> 19:38.354
Drink up, captain.
We move out at dawn.

